6 An Act relating to professions and occupations;
enacting the Dentist and Dental Hygienist Compact and
7 authorizing the Governor to enter into the Compact
with certain jurisdictions; setting forth form of the
8 Compact; providing for codification; and providing an
effective date.
9
10
11
12 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
13 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
14 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 329.1 of Title 59, unless there
15 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
16 The Dentist and Dental Hygienist Compact is hereby enacted into
17 law and the Governor shall enter into the Compact on behalf of the
18 State of Oklahoma with any jurisdiction legally joined therein, in
19 the form substantially as set forth in this act.
20 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
21 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 329.2 of Title 59, unless there
22 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
23 DENTIST AND DENTAL HYGIENIST COMPACT
24 SECTION 1: TITLE AND PURPOSE
ENGR. S. B. NO. 540 Page 1

1 This statute shall be known and cited as the “Dentist and Dental
2 Hygienist Compact”. The purposes of this Compact are to facilitate
3 the interstate practice of dentistry and dental hygiene and improve
4 public access to dentistry and dental hygiene services by providing
5 Dentists and Dental Hygienists licensed in a Participating State the
6 ability to practice in Participating States in which they are not
7 licensed. The Compact does this by establishing a pathway for
8 Dentists and Dental Hygienists licensed in a Participating State to
9 obtain a Compact Privilege that authorizes them to practice in
10 another Participating State in which they are not licensed. The
11 Compact enables Participating States to protect the public health
12 and safety with respect to the practice of such Dentists and Dental
13 Hygienists, through the State’s authority to regulate the practice
14 of dentistry and dental hygiene in the State. The Compact:
15 A. Enables Dentists and Dental Hygienists who qualify for a
16 Compact Privilege to practice in other Participating States without
17 satisfying burdensome and duplicative requirements associated with
18 securing a License to practice in those States.
19 B. Promotes mobility and addresses workforce shortages through
20 each Participating State’s acceptance of a Compact Privilege to
21 practice in that State.
22 C. Increases public access to qualified, licensed Dentists and
23 Dental Hygienists by creating a responsible, streamlined pathway for
24 Licensees to practice in Participating States.
ENGR. S. B. NO. 540 Page 2

1 D. Enhances the ability of Participating States to protect the
2 public’s health and safety.
3 E. Does not interfere with licensure requirements established
4 by a Participating State.
5 F. Facilitates the sharing of licensure and disciplinary
6 information among Participating States.
7 G. Requires Dentists and Dental Hygienists who practice in a
8 Participating State pursuant to a Compact Privilege to practice
9 within the Scope of Practice authorized in that State.
10 H. Extends the authority of a Participating State to regulate
11 the practice of dentistry and dental hygiene within its borders to
12 Dentists and Dental Hygienists who practice in the State through a
13 Compact Privilege.
14 I. Promotes the cooperation of Participating States in
15 regulating the practice of dentistry and dental hygiene within those
16 States.
17 J. Facilitates the relocation of military members and their
18 spouses who are licensed to practice dentistry or dental hygiene.
19 SECTION 2: DEFINITIONS
20 As used in this Compact, unless the context requires otherwise,
21 the following definitions shall apply:
22 A. “Active Military Member” means any person with full-time
23 duty status in the armed forces of the United States, including
24 members of the National Guard and Reserve.
ENGR. S. B. NO. 540 Page 3

1 B. “Adverse Action” means disciplinary action or encumbrance
2 imposed on a License or Compact Privilege by a State Licensing
3 Authority.
4 C. “Alternative Program” means a non-disciplinary monitoring or
5 practice remediation process applicable to a Dentist or Dental
6 Hygienist approved by a State Licensing Authority of a Participating
7 State in which the Dentist or Dental Hygienist is licensed. This
8 includes, but is not limited to, programs to which Licensees with
9 substance abuse or addiction issues are referred in lieu of Adverse
10 Action.
11 D. “Clinical Assessment” means examination or process, required
12 for licensure as a Dentist or Dental Hygienist as applicable, that
13 provides evidence of clinical competence in dentistry or dental
14 hygiene.
15 E. “Commissioner” means the individual appointed by a
16 Participating State to serve as the member of the Commission for
17 that Participating State.
18 F. “Compact” means this Dentist and Dental Hygienist Compact.
19 G. “Compact Privilege” means the authorization granted by a
20 Remote State to allow a Licensee from a Participating State to
21 practice as a Dentist or Dental Hygienist in a Remote State.
22 H. “Continuing Professional Development” means a requirement,
23 as a condition of License renewal, to provide evidence of successful
24
ENGR. S. B. NO. 540 Page 4

1 part icipation in educational or professional activities relevant to
2 practice or area of work.
3 I. “Criminal Background Check” means the submission of
4 fingerprints or other biometric-based information for a License
5 applicant for the purpose of obtaining that applicant’s criminal
6 history record information, as defined in 28 C.F.R., Section 20.3(d)
7 from the Federal Bureau of Investigation and the State’s criminal
8 history record repository as defined in 28 C.F.R., Section 20.3(f).
9 J. “Data System” means the Commission’s repository of
10 information about Licensees, including but not limited to
11 examination, licensure, investigative, Compact Privilege, Adverse
12 Action, and Alternative Program.
13 K. “Dental Hygienist” means an individual who is licensed by a
14 State Licensing Authority to practice dental hygiene.
15 L. “Dentist” means an individual who is licensed by a State
16 Licensing Authority to practice dentistry.
17 M. “Dentist and Dental Hygienist Compact Commission” or
18 “Commission” means a joint government agency established by this
19 Compact comprised of each State that has enacted the Compact and a
20 national administrative body comprised of a Commissioner from each
21 State that has enacted the Compact.
22 N. “Encumbered License” means a License that a State Licensing
23 Authority has limited in any way other than through an Alternative
24 Program.
ENGR. S. B. NO. 540 Page 5

1 O. “Executive Board” means the Chair, Vice Chair, Secretary and
2 Treasurer and any other Commissioners as may be determined by
3 Commission Rule or bylaw.
4 P. “Jurisprudence Requirement” means the assessment of an
5 individual’s knowledge of the laws and Rules governing the practice
6 of dentistry or dental hygiene, as applicable, in a State.
7 Q. “License” means current authorization by a State, other than
8 authorization pursuant to a Compact Privilege, or other privilege,
9 for an individual to practice as a Dentist or Dental Hygienist in
10 that State.
11 R. “Licensee” means an individual who holds an unrestricted
12 License from a Participating State to practice as a Dentist or
13 Dental Hygienist in that State.
14 S. “Model Compact” means the model for the Dentist and Dental
15 Hygienist Compact on file with the Council of State Governments or
16 other entity as designated by the Commission.
17 T. “Participating State” means a State that has enacted the
18 Compact and been admitted to the Commission in accordance with the
19 provisions herein and Commission Rules.
20 U. “Qualifying License” means a License that is not an
21 Encumbered License issued by a Participating State to practice
22 dentistry or dental hygiene.
23
24
ENGR. S. B. NO. 540 Page 6

1 V. “Remote State” means a Participating State where a Licensee
2 who is not licensed as a Dentist or Dental Hygienist is exercising
3 or seeking to exercise the Compact Privilege.
4 W. “Rule” means a regulation promulgated by an entity that has
5 the force of law.
6 X. “Scope of Practice” means the procedures, actions, and
7 processes a Dentist or Dental Hygienist licensed in a State is
8 permitted to undertake in that State and the circumstances under
9 which the Licensee is permitted to undertake those procedures,
10 actions and processes. Such procedures, actions and processes and
11 the circumstances under which they may be undertaken may be
12 established through means, including, but not limited to, statute,
13 regulations, case law, and other processes available to the State
14 Licensing Authority or other government agency.
15 Y. “Significant Investigative Information” means information,
16 records, and documents received or generated by a State Licensing
17 Authority pursuant to an investigation for which a determination has
18 been made that there is probable cause to believe that the Licensee
19 has violated a statute or regulation that is considered more than a
20 minor infraction for which the State Licensing Authority could
21 pursue Adverse Action against the Licensee.
22 Z. “State” means any state, commonwealth, district, or
23 territory of the United States of America that regulates the
24 practices of dentistry and dental hygiene.
ENGR. S. B. NO. 540 Page 7

1 AA. “State Licensing Authority” means an agency or other entity
2 of a State that is responsible for the licensing and regulation of
3 Dentists or Dental Hygienists.
4 SECTION 3: STATE PARTICIPATION IN THE COMPACT
5 A. In order to join the Compact and thereafter continue as a
6 Participating State, a State must:
7 1. Enact a compact that is not materially different from the
8 Model Compact as determined in accordance with Commission Rules;
9 2. Participate fully in the Commission’s Data System;
10 3. Have a mechanism in place for receiving and investigating
11 complaints about its Licensees and License applicants;
12 4. Notify the Commission, in compliance with the terms of the
13 Compact and Commission Rules, of any Adverse Action or the
14 availability of Significant Investigative Information regarding a
15 Licensee and License applicant;
16 5. Fully implement a Criminal Background Check requirement,
17 within a time frame established by Commission Rule, by receiving the
18 results of a qualifying Criminal Background Check;
19 6. Comply with the Commission Rules applicable to a
20 Participating State;
21 7. Accept the National Board Examinations of the Joint
22 Commission on National Dental Examinations or another examination
23 accepted by Commission Rule as a licensure examination;
24
ENGR. S. B. NO. 540 Page 8

1 8. Accept for licensure that applicants for a Dentist License
2 graduate from a predoctoral dental education program accredited by
3 the Commission on Dental Accreditation, or another accrediting
4 agency recognized by the United States Department of Education for
5 the accreditation of dentistry and dental hygiene education
6 programs, leading to the Doctor of Dental Surgery (D.D.S.) or Doctor
7 of Dental Medicine (D.M.D.) degree;
8 9. Accept for licensure that applicants for a Dental Hygienist
9 License graduate from a dental hygiene education program accredited
10 by the Commission on Dental Accreditation or another accrediting
11 agency recognized by the United States Department of Education for
12 the accreditation of dentistry and dental hygiene education
13 programs;
14 10. Require for licensure that applicants successfully complete
15 a Clinical Assessment;
16 11. Have Continuing Professional Development requirements as a
17 condition for License renewal; and
18 12. Pay a participation fee to the Commission as established by
19 Commission Rule.
20 B. Providing alternative pathways for an individual to obtain
21 an unrestricted License does not disqualify a State from
22 participating in the Compact.
23 C. When conducting a Criminal Background Check the State
24 Licensing Authority shall:
ENGR. S. B. NO. 540 Page 9

1 1. Consider that information in making a licensure decision;
2 2. Maintain documentation of completion of the Criminal
3 Background Check and background check information to the extent
4 allowed by State and federal law; and
5 3. Report to the Commission whether it has completed the
6 Criminal Background Check and whether the individual was granted or
7 denied a License.
8 D. A Licensee of a Participating State who has a Qualifying
9 License in that State and does not hold an Encumbered License in any
10 other Participating State, shall be issued a Compact Privilege in a
11 Remote State in accordance with the terms of the Compact and
12 Commission Rules. If a Remote State has a Jurisprudence Requirement
13 a Compact Privilege will not be issued to the Licensee unless the
14 Licensee has satisfied the Jurisprudence Requirement.
15 SECTION 4: COMPACT PRIVILEGE
16 A. To obtain and exercise the Compact Privilege under the terms
17 and provisions of the Compact, the Licensee shall:
18 1. Have a Qualifying License as a Dentist or Dental Hygienist
19 in a Participating State;
20 2. Be eligible for a Compact Privilege in any Remote State in
21 accordance with subsections D, G and H of this section;
22 3. Submit to an application process whenever the Licensee is
23 seeking a Compact Privilege;
24
ENGR. S. B. NO. 540 Page 10

1 4. Pay any applicable Commission and Remote State fees for a
2 Compact Privilege in the Remote State;
3 5. Meet any Jurisprudence Requirement established by a Remote
4 State in which the Licensee is seeking a Compact Privilege;
5 6. Have passed a National Board Examination of the Joint
6 Commission on National Dental Examinations or another examination
7 accepted by Commission Rule;
8 7. For a Dentist, have graduated from a predoctoral dental
9 education program accredited by the Commission on Dental
10 Accreditation, or another accrediting agency recognized by the
11 United States Department of Education for the accreditation of
12 dentistry and dental hygiene education programs, leading to the
13 Doctor of Dental Surgery (D.D.S.) or Doctor of Dental Medicine
14 (D.M.D.) degree;
15 8. For a Dental Hygienist, have graduated from a dental hygiene
16 education program accredited by the Commission on Dental
17 Accreditation or another accrediting agency recognized by the United
18 States Department of Education for the accreditation of dentistry
19 and dental hygiene education programs;
20 9. Have successfully completed a Clinical Assessment for
21 licensure;
22 10. Report to the Commission Adverse Action taken by any non-
23 Participating State when applying for a Compact Privilege and,
24
ENGR. S. B. NO. 540 Page 11

1 othe rwise, within thirty (30) days from the date the Adverse Action
2 is taken;
3 11. Report to the Commission when applying for a Compact
4 Privilege the address of the Licensee’s primary residence and
5 thereafter immediately report to the Commission any change in the
6 address of the Licensee’s primary residence; and
7 12. Consent to accept service of process by mail at the
8 Licensee’s primary residence on record with the Commission with
9 respect to any action brought against the Licensee by the Commission
10 or a Participating State, and consent to accept service of a
11 subpoena by mail at the Licensee’s primary residence on record with
12 the Commission with respect to any action brought or investigation
13 conducted by the Commission or a Participating State.
14 B. The Licensee must comply with the requirements of subsection
15 A of this section to maintain the Compact Privilege in the Remote
16 State. If those requirements are met, the Compact Privilege will
17 continue as long as the Licensee maintains a Qualifying License in
18 the State through which the Licensee applied for the Compact
19 Privilege and pays any applicable Compact Privilege renewal fees.
20 C. A Licensee providing dentistry or dental hygiene in a Remote
21 State under the Compact Privilege shall function within the Scope of
22 Practice authorized by the Remote State for a Dentist or Dental
23 Hygienist licensed in that State.
24
ENGR. S. B. NO. 540 Page 12

1 D. A Licensee providing dentistry or dental hygiene pursuant to
2 a Compact Privilege in a Remote State is subject to that State’s
3 regulatory authority. A Remote State may, in accordance with due
4 process and that State’s laws, by Adverse Action revoke or remove a
5 Licensee’s Compact Privilege in the Remote State for a specific
6 period of time and impose fines or take any other necessary actions
7 to protect the health and safety of its citizens. If a Remote State
8 imposes an Adverse Action against a Compact Privilege that limits
9 the Compact Privilege, that Adverse Action applies to all Compact
10 Privileges in all Remote States. A Licensee whose Compact Privilege
11 in a Remote State is removed for a specified period of time is not
12 eligible for a Compact Privilege in any other Remote State until the
13 specific time for removal of the Compact Privilege has passed and
14 all encumbrance requirements are satisfied.
15 E. If a License in a Participating State is an Encumbered
16 License, the Licensee shall lose the Compact Privilege in a Remote
17 State and shall not be eligible for a Compact Privilege in any
18 Remote State until the License is no longer encumbered.
19 F. Once an Encumbered License in a Participating State is
20 restored to good standing, the Licensee must meet the requirements
21 of subsection A of this section to obtain a Compact Privilege in a
22 Remote State.
23 G. If a Licensee’s Compact Privilege in a Remote State is
24 removed by the Remote State, the individual shall lose or be
ENGR. S. B. NO. 540 Page 13

1 inel igible for the Compact Privilege in any Remote State until the
2 following occur:
3 1. The specific period of time for which the Compact Privilege
4 was removed has ended; and
5 2. All conditions for removal of the Compact Privilege have
6 been satisfied.
7 H. Once the requirements of subsection G of this section have
8 been met, the Licensee must meet the requirements in subsection A of
9 this section to obtain a Compact Privilege in a Remote State.
10 SECTION 5: ACTIVE MILITARY MEMBER OR THEIR SPOUSES
11 An Active Military Member and their spouse shall not be required
12 to pay to the Commission for a Compact Privilege the fee otherwise
13 charged by the Commission. If a Remote State chooses to charge a
14 fee for a Compact Privilege, it may choose to charge a reduced fee
15 or no fee to an Active Military Member and their spouse for a
16 Compact Privilege.
17 SECTION 6: ADVERSE ACTIONS
18 A. A Participating State in which a Licensee is licensed shall
19 have exclusive authority to impose Adverse Action against the
20 Qualifying License issued by that Participating State.
21 B. A Participating State may take Adverse Action based on the
22 Significant Investigative Information of a Remote State, so long as
23 the Participating State follows its own procedures for imposing
24 Adverse Action.
ENGR. S. B. NO. 540 Page 14

1 C. Nothing in this Compact shall override a Participating
2 State’s decision that participation in an Alternative Program may be
3 used in lieu of Adverse Action and that such participation shall
4 remain non-public if required by the Participating State’s laws.
5 Participating States must require Licensees who enter any
6 Alternative Program in lieu of discipline to agree not to practice
7 pursuant to a Compact Privilege in any other Participating State
8 during the term of the Alternative Program without prior
9 authorization from such other Participating State.
10 D. Any Participating State in which a Licensee is applying to
11 practice or is practicing pursuant to a Compact Privilege may
12 investigate actual or alleged violations of the statutes and
13 regulations authorizing the practice of dentistry or dental hygiene
14 in any other Participating State in which the Dentist or Dental
15 Hygienist holds a License or Compact Privilege.
16 E. A Remote State shall have the authority to:
17 1. Take Adverse Actions as set forth in Section 4.D against a
18 Licensee’s Compact Privilege in the State;
19 2. In furtherance of its rights and responsibilities under the
20 Compact and the Commission’s Rules, issue subpoenas for both
21 hearings and investigations that require the attendance and
22 testimony of witnesses, and the production of evidence. Subpoenas
23 issued by a State Licensing Authority in a Participating State for
24 the attendance and testimony of witnesses, or the production of
ENGR. S. B. NO. 540 Page 15

1 evid ence from another Participating State, shall be enforced in the
2 latter State by any court of competent jurisdiction, according to
3 the practice and procedure of that court applicable to subpoenas
4 issued in proceedings pending before it. The issuing authority
5 shall pay any witness fees, travel expenses, mileage, and other fees
6 required by the service statutes of the State where the witnesses or
7 evidence are located; and
8 3. If otherwise permitted by State law, recover from the
9 Licensee the costs of investigations and disposition of cases
10 resulting from any Adverse Action taken against that Licensee.
11 F. Joint Investigations.
12 1. In addition to the authority granted to a Participating
13 State by its Dentist or Dental Hygienist licensure act or other
14 applicable State law, a Participating State may jointly investigate
15 Licensees with other Participating States.
16 2. Participating States shall share any Significant
17 Investigative Information, litigation, or compliance materials in
18 furtherance of any joint or individual investigation initiated under
19 the Compact.
20 G. Authority to Continue Investigation.
21 1. After a Licensee’s Compact Privilege in a Remote State is
22 terminated, the Remote State may continue an investigation of the
23 Licensee that began when the Licensee had a Compact Privilege in
24 that Remote State.
ENGR. S. B. NO. 540 Page 16

1 2. If the investigation yields what would be Significant
2 Investigative Information had the Licensee continued to have a
3 Compact Privilege in that Remote State, the Remote State shall
4 report the presence of such information to the Data System as
5 required by Section 8.B.6 as if it was Significant Investigative
6 Information.
7 SECTION 7: ESTABLISHMENT AND OPERATION OF THE COMMISSION
8 A. The Compact Participating States hereby create and establish
9 a joint government agency whose membership consists of all
10 Participating States that have enacted the Compact. The Commission
11 is an instrumentality of the Participating States acting jointly and
12 not an instrumentality of any one State. The Commission shall come
13 into existence on or after the effective date of the Compact as set
14 forth in Section 11.A.
15 B. Participation, Voting, and Meetings.
16 1. Each Participating State shall have and be limited to one
17 (1) Commissioner selected by that Participating State’s State
18 Licensing Authority or, if the State has more than one State
19 Licensing Authority, selected collectively by the State Licensing
20 Authorities.
21 2. The Commissioner shall be a member or designee of such
22 Authority or Authorities.
23
24
ENGR. S. B. NO. 540 Page 17

1 3. The Commission may by Rule or bylaw establish a term of
2 office for Commissioners and may by Rule or bylaw establish term
3 limits.
4 4. The Commission may recommend to a State Licensing Authority
5 or Authorities, as applicable, removal or suspension of an
6 individual as the State’s Commissioner.
7 5. A Participating State’s State Licensing Authority, or
8 Authorities, as applicable, shall fill any vacancy of its
9 Commissioner on the Commission within sixty (60) days of the
10 vacancy.
11 6. Each Commissioner shall be entitled to one vote on all
12 matters that are voted upon by the Commission.
13 7. The Commission shall meet at least once during each calendar
14 year. Additional meetings may be held as set forth in the bylaws.
15 The Commission may meet by telecommunication, video conference or
16 other similar electronic means.
17 C. The Commission shall have the following powers:
18 1. Establish the fiscal year of the Commission;
19 2. Establish a code of conduct and conflict of interest
20 policies;
21 3. Adopt Rules and bylaws;
22 4. Maintain its financial records in accordance with the
23 bylaws;
24
